To be as literal and close as the difference between the languages would admit, has been the aim throughout. But there are occasions, as every scholar knOWS, where to be faithful to the letter is to be most unfaithful to the spirit of an author 3 and where to be close is to be hope- lessly prosaiC. Phrases, nay, single words, and names, rich in association5‚ and full of poetical suggestiveness in one language, are bald, if not absolutely without sig- nificance, in another. BesideS‚ even under the most skilful hands, a thought or sentiment must at times be expanded or condensed to meet the necessity of the stanza. The triumph of the translator is, where this is effected without losing any of the significance, or clash- ing with the pervading sentiment, of the original. In the translations of others who have made it their aim Δ to imitate the Classical formS, the present *translator does not find that, upon the whole, they escape the danger of either adding to or subtracting from the language of the original which besets the translator who adopts the more familiar forms of English verse. Such translators are, moreover, apt to forget that it is English verse, and for English readerS, they are writing. Thus they fall into the vices of a hybrid style, neither Latin nor English, in which, to use old George Chapman's words—-
